## Generating Random Numbers
Functions for probability functions
d: density
r: random number generator
p: cumulative distribution
q: quantile function

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxucm5vcm0oMTAsIDUsIDEpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
rnorm(10, 5, 1)
 [1] 6.292343 4.850359 5.858479 4.471644 4.665887 3.975539 3.702691 5.463754 6.329480
[10] 4.596794
```r
dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd=1, log = FALSE)
pnorm(q, mean = 0, sd=1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)
qnorm(p, mean = 0, sd=1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)
rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd=1)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

pnorm(q) = f(q) ==> P(x < q)
qnorm(p) = f'(p)

q...(): probability distribution functions beginning with the `q' prefix are used to evaluate the quantile (inverse cumulative distribution) function.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxueCA8LSBybm9ybSgxMClcbnN1bW1hcnkoeClcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
x <- rnorm(10)
summary(x)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

# simulate a linear model
Generate data from a linear model

y = b0 + b1x + e; e~N(0, 4) and x~N(0,1), 
b0=0.5  and b1=2


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMjApXG5cbnggPC0gcm5vcm0oMTAwKVxuZSA8LSBybm9ybSgxMDAsIDAsIDIpXG55IDwtIDAuNSArIDIqeCArIGVcbnN1bW1hcnkoeSlcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
set.seed(20)

x <- rnorm(100)
e <- rnorm(100, 0, 2)
y <- 0.5 + 2*x + e
summary(y)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

What if x is binary?

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMTApXG5cbnggPC0gcmJpbm9tKDEwMCwgMSwgMC41KVxuZSA8LSBybm9ybSgxMDAsIDAsIDIpXG55IDwtIDAuNSArIDIqeCArIGVcblxuc3VtbWFyeSh5KVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
set.seed(10)

x <- rbinom(100, 1, 0.5)
e <- rnorm(100, 0, 2)
y <- 0.5 + 2*x + e

summary(y)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

# Generating Random Numbers from a Generalized Linear Model

suppose we want to simulate from a Poisson model where
Y ~ Poisson(m)    log(m) = b0 + b1*x
b0 = 0.5  and b1 = 0.3


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuc2V0LnNlZWQoMSlcblxueCA8LSBybm9ybSgxMDApXG5sb2cubXUgPC0gMC41ICsgMC4zKnhcblxueSA8LSBycG9pcygxMDAsIGV4cChsb2cubXUpKVxuXG5wbG90KHgsIHkpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
set.seed(1)

x <- rnorm(100)
log.mu <- 0.5 + 0.3*x

y <- rpois(100, exp(log.mu))

plot(x, y)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

## Profiling

We need to optimize our code when we work with large datasets and if we need to run loop for 1000 iterations. But dont forget premature optimization is the root of all evil.

First collect data, dont guess.

system.time() takes an argument and computes the time (in seconds) spent by the CPU to execute an expression.
* It returns an object of class proc_time.
* If a computer has more than one available processor and R is able to take advantage of that, then which of the following is true when using `system.time()' 
 
## Elapsed time > user time
system.time(readLines("http://www.jhsph.edu"))
hilbert <- function(n) {
    i <- 1:n
    1/outer(i-1, i, "+")
}

x <- hilbert(1000)

system.time(svd(x))
system.time({
    n <- 1000
    r <- numeric()
    for (i in 1:n) {
        x <- rnorm(n)
        r[i] <- mean(x)
    }
})

Rprofiler

Rprof() summaryRprof() DO not use system.time() and Rprof() together!!!

summaryRprof() summarizes the output of Rprof() and gives percent of time spent in each function (two types of normalization)

It is good to break the code into functions…

Quiz

set.seed(1)
rpois(5,2)
